  "What does 'optimization' mean in calculus?": "",
  "Graphing the function accurately": "",
  "Finding where the function equals zero": "",
  "Making a function faster": "",
  "Finding the maximum or minimum value of a function, often subject to constraints": "",
  "Optimization uses derivatives to find where a function attains its maximum or minimum value. Set f'(x) = 0 and check whether the critical point is a max, min, or neither.": "",
  "What is a 'critical point'?": "",
  "A point where f'(x) = 0 or f'(x) is undefined": "",
  "The endpoints of the domain": "",
  "A point where f is discontinuous": "",
  "A point where f(x) = 0": "",
  "Critical points are where f'(x) = 0 or f'(x) doesn't exist. Local maxima and minima can only occur at critical points (or endpoints of a closed interval).": "",
  "What is the 'closed interval method' for finding absolute extrema?": "",
  "Use the second derivative test at every point according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Only check where f'(x) = 0 under most circumstances involving absolute": "",
  "Only check the endpoints under most circumstances involving absolute": "",
  "Evaluate f at critical points and endpoints; the largest is the absolute max, smallest is the absolute min": "",
  "On a closed interval [a,b]: find all critical points, evaluate f at each critical point and at both endpoints. Compare values to find the absolute maximum and minimum.": "",
  "What does the 'second derivative test' determine?": "",
  "The absolute maximum and minimum": "",
  "Whether the function is increasing or decreasing": "",
  "Whether a critical point is a local max (f'' < 0) or local min (f'' > 0)": "",
  "Whether the function is concave up or down everywhere": "",
  "At a critical point where f'(c) = 0: if f''(c) > 0, it's a local minimum; if f''(c) < 0, it's a local maximum; if f''(c) = 0, the test is inconclusive.": "",
  "What does 'constraint' mean in optimization?": "",
  "The derivative of the objective function": "",
  "The domain of the function": "",
  "The function to be maximized": "",
  "A condition that limits the possible values of the variables": "",
  "A constraint is an equation or inequality that the variables must satisfy (like 'the perimeter is 40' or 'the volume is 1000'). Use it to eliminate a variable before optimizing.": "",
  "What is an 'objective function'?": "",
  "The derivative of the constraint": "",
  "Any function with a maximum": "",
  "The function you want to maximize or minimize": "",
  "The constraint equation": "",
  "The objective function is the quantity you want to optimize (maximize or minimize), such as area, cost, profit, or distance.": "",
  "What is a 'local maximum'?": "",
  "The largest value of f on its entire domain": "",
  "A point where f(c) is larger than f(x) for all x near c": "",
  "A point where f'(c) > 0": "",
  "A point where f(c) > 0": "",
  "A local maximum at x = c means f(c) >= f(x) for all x in some neighborhood of c. It's the highest point locally, though not necessarily the highest on the entire domain.": "",
  "What does 'absolute minimum' mean?": "",
  "The smallest value of f(x) over its entire domain": "",
  "The smallest positive value of f": "",
  "Where f'(x) is smallest": "",
  "The absolute (global) minimum is the smallest value f achieves on its entire domain. On a closed interval, it occurs at a critical point or an endpoint.": "",
  "What does 'feasible region' mean in optimization?": "",
  "Where the derivative is positive": "",
  "The set of all values that satisfy the constraints": "",
  "The graph of the objective function": "",
  "The range of the function": "",
  "The feasible region is the set of all (x, y, ...) values that satisfy all given constraints. The optimal solution must lie within this region.": "",
  "What does 'endpoint' mean for optimization on an interval?": "",
  "Where the function equals zero": "",
  "The critical points only": "",
  "The inflection points": "",
  "The boundary values of the interval where the function is defined": "",
  "Endpoints are the boundary values a and b of a closed interval [a,b]. Absolute extrema can occur at endpoints, so they must always be checked.": "",
  "A company manufactures boxes to ship products. Each box must have a volume of 500 cm^3 with a square base. What base dimension minimizes the surface area?": "",
